title: Bender
name: joey100782
comments: [["Great example of multicolor using filament changes! Bender looks much more realistic than printing all in one color.Your design and sequencing of each color layer is exceptionally well done. With three or more colors, color stripes from lower layers may be visible on components in upper layers, particularly when viewing the object from the side. By placing the white and silver (very similar colors) layers together, the thin white layer on the silver bottoms is not noticeable. Also, offsetting from a black bottom base avoided black stripes in the silver parts, and it created a nice outline as well, very much like the Bender cartoon character.I've added your thing to my Design: Multicolor Filament Collection, to help other Thingiverse designers better understand how adding color can make a good thing look great."]]

[["Beautiful work. I'd like to learn more about how you painted it. I've painted a few basic things, but nothing as complex as your work here.Paints? Brushes? Guides or shields to keep paint off wrong surface?", "Thanks for reaching out! I'm glad you like the plant.
Actually, with valentine's day around the corner, I was already quite late with painting and uploading the model so I cut some corners and started with a bigger brush (size 2) than I usually do. I switched to a smaller brush (size 0) for repairing mistakes and working on a few details later.If I remember correctly, this is roughly what I did:1.) Applying a rather thick primer in order to smooth out the most visible print lines. (cheap spray can from the hardware store)
2.) I painted a base coat of brown, green (light/dark), orange and magenta acrylic paints and tried to make that green gradient work. ;-) (vallejo model color)
3.) Repairing the most visible mistakes with a smaller brush.
4.) Applying some washes (red/green/sepia) for 'quick' shadows.
5.) Dry-brushing everything with bit of white acrylic paint to make the highlights more visible.
6.) I then slightly brushed over the highlights with watered down colors (red/green/yellow) in order to dye the white highlights.
7.) In a last step I applied some speedpaints (red/green/yellow) here and there in order to enhance some of the shadows and saturation. (army painter speedpaint) (Inks would probably have worked just as well - but I don't have those. ;-) )Hope this helps.WOW. Yes! Thanks for your detailed explanation. It's probably the best description of painting 3D objects I've seen on the Thingiverse.Thanks, I'm glad it is useful. :-)
Thinking about it, there is one thing I'd like to add: Most of this is roughly following a common standard workflow for miniature painting. If I had a little more time, I'd probably had skipped the dry brushing on this model and had painted the highlight my hand, instead. Here is why:
As this is a FDM print (PLA) the layer lines are rather prominent. Dry brushing enhances small details, so with FDM prints there is always the danger of making these more visible (instead of the actual details in the model). However since I was in a hurry and this technique is extremely fast, I still resorted to it. Luckily the primer filled most of the layer lines so this still worked good enough. :-)", "WOW. Yes! Thanks for your detailed explanation. It's probably the best description of painting 3D objects I've seen on the Thingiverse.Thanks, I'm glad it is useful. :-)
Thinking about it, there is one thing I'd like to add: Most of this is roughly following a common standard workflow for miniature painting. If I had a little more time, I'd probably had skipped the dry brushing on this model and had painted the highlight my hand, instead. Here is why:
As this is a FDM print (PLA) the layer lines are rather prominent. Dry brushing enhances small details, so with FDM prints there is always the danger of making these more visible (instead of the actual details in the model). However since I was in a hurry and this technique is extremely fast, I still resorted to it. Luckily the primer filled most of the layer lines so this still worked good enough. :-)", "Thanks, I'm glad it is useful. :-)
Thinking about it, there is one thing I'd like to add: Most of this is roughly following a common standard workflow for miniature painting. If I had a little more time, I'd probably had skipped the dry brushing on this model and had painted the highlight my hand, instead. Here is why:
As this is a FDM print (PLA) the layer lines are rather prominent. Dry brushing enhances small details, so with FDM prints there is always the danger of making these more visible (instead of the actual details in the model). However since I was in a hurry and this technique is extremely fast, I still resorted to it. Luckily the primer filled most of the layer lines so this still worked good enough. :-)"]]

title: Bender
name: joey100782
comments: [["Great example of multicolor using filament changes! Bender looks much more realistic than printing all in one color.Your design and sequencing of each color layer is exceptionally well done. With three or more colors, color stripes from lower layers may be visible on components in upper layers, particularly when viewing the object from the side. By placing the white and silver (very similar colors) layers together, the thin white layer on the silver bottoms is not noticeable. Also, offsetting from a black bottom base avoided black stripes in the silver parts, and it created a nice outline as well, very much like the Bender cartoon character.I've added your thing to my Design: Multicolor Filament Collection, to help other Thingiverse designers better understand how adding color can make a good thing look great."]]

title: Customizable airfoil data based toroidal multi loop propellers (print friendly)
name: Parkinbot
comments: [["Interesting. I hadn't heard of these before. I would think that the rotation speed of a drone propeller might stress or deform the ring shape due to the huge centrifugal forces involved.I might try remixing this to see how it works on my over-engineered pullcopter. For that project I also had to first complete another project to create a prop blade model, which transitions between three NACA airfoils from root to tip. For a toroidal propeller pullcopter, I wonder if any increase in efficiency would overcome what appears to be an increase in weight and possibly drag.", 'Since that guy from MIT won his award with a toroidal propeller design loop propellers are becoming increasingly popular. Especially in the copter community. However there are no specific design rules out there as the aerodynamics has not been studied extensively. So everyone interested copies what he finds in the net and tries or adds some modifications – starting from skewed plain rings without any aerodynamic profiles. But - from the point of material strength and smoothness - even with proper airfoil data it seems a bit hopeless trying to use FDA prints to compete against industrial blade designs. However, the community will produce a wide variety of experimental results and that will surely advance the story.']]

I really appreciate the feedback.This was designed for the Kickstarter sleeves, but maybe differences in printers or in sleeve thickness from batch to batch. There are more craftable items then purchasable and random, so that side is quite tight. I originally split them evenly but decided later to fit all craftable items on one side. I will probably just create new dividers that have available items first and unavailable afterwards, but you could also make the holder longer and add a spacer on the purchasable side.Np, thx. I did elongate it slightly then I used calipers to measure my decks. I found my challenge deck needed 30mm but I could only make it 29. It fits but a little tight. In prudaslicer I added a negitive modifier block that’s 29mm then put it in the area so it cuts a bit of the divider and back wall. This is a cool way to enlarge a space but it’s tricky to get the block exactly where you need it.Another thing I did was make a cut of the top of the model. title: Charge balancing holder
name: AskerKazharov
comments: [['Для баланса батареи должны соединяться последовательно - для этого в макете должен быть предусмотрен симметричный метод вставки батарей. Второе: учитывая, что конструкция относительно жёсткая, батареи надо чем-то подпружинивать, иначе они тупо разомкнутся.\nСама конструкция - она конечно же разборная? :) (на случай, если мне надо только 6 батареек)', 'Жаль, что ничего не понимаете в схемотехнике. Очень жаль. Но если оттопырите пальчики и посмотрите видео, прежде чем писать глупый комментарий, то Вам откроется истина, а именно: школьная физика 8-9 класса, где сказано о возникновении тока при разности потенциалов, а также узрите и без того очевидную по 3D модели пружинистость объекта. И в момент этого откровения, которое откроется Вам при включении 2 извилины, в голове накопится достаточное количество активных нейронов, которые соединившись в более сложную сеть, выдадут мысль, что необзодимости в разборе нет и достаточно положить 6 батареек, оставив пустыми остальные 4, и ничего более не надо городить с последовательными соединениями, с симметричными вставками и т.д, вызывая хохот и стыд у своего школьного учителя по физике.\nНе перестану удивляться людям, которым важно написать кислотный комментарий, даже не разобравшись в предмете обсуждения и не посмотрев предложенные материалы, которые он критикует с высоты своего мракобесия.Поразительный по занудности идиот! Мог бы не напрягать последнюю извилину для своего пустопорожнего коммента.', 'Поразительный по занудности идиот! Мог бы не напрягать последнюю извилину для своего пустопорожнего коммента.']]

title: Spool Holder for SOVOL SV06 3d printer
name: rogerquin
comments: [['Thank you printing now'], ["I need help...I'm definitely doing something wrong. I got very excited because this was the longest successful print job that my SV06 has completed...but as soon as I went to assemble the pieces together...the tolerances were too tight and the screw threads wouldn't work properly. I put the adapter over the two-piece collar, but it was so tight that it only made it halfway before being unable to fit any further...and then when I went to separate the pieces...the adapter broke across a layer line rather than slip back off the collar.I printed using Polymaker Tough PETG...is that this issue? Should I just use regular PLA? Please help me out. I'm really bummed that a 16 hour print is useless due to some error on my part.", "I'm sorry to hear that, Preston. Don't be bummed. Solving the issues is part of the fun. If you saw my video, you can see that there is plenty of clearance, so, my guess is that somewhere in your software or hardware, or both, the calibration is off. PLA is forgiving of course, and that's a good material to start with when calibrating. Create a basic cylinder with a 50mm diameter and 10 or 20mm high and print it at 0.2mm layer height. Then pull out your caliper and see where your dimensions fall. If they're off, then you know you have to calibrate. Once all looks good, try printing only the section of the spool that gave you trouble and go from there. Troubleshooting small sections will save you lots of time and waste less filament. I hope you find my info helpful. which slicer are you using btw?Sounds good. I'll run some calibration tests and see if I need to set my mm/s steps for my X, Y, Z, and Extruder a bit different. That was my thought in the end was that I was probably over-extruding with the PETG. My Extrusion Multiplier for PLA is 1.03, but that might be different with a material with different properties. As far as slicer goes, I have been using mostly Prusaslicer 2.5.0, but I just downloaded Cura 5.2.2 and that's what I used for the print of your Thing. I'll get back to you and let you know if any adjustments were necessary and, if I end up attempting the spool holder in PETG again, I'll let you know if it comes out alright. Thanks for taking the time to reply to my request for help!!! - PrestonI'm using SuperSlicer ( basically the same as PrusaSlicer ). I'm using the M221 S command in my start gcode instead of the Extrusion Multiplier, but if I was to use the M221 value in the Extrusion Multiplier, it would be around 0.9 which is very different than yours. Have you tried a single-wall calibration with your current settings?Yeah, I'm working on a 40mm single-walled open cube for calibrating the Extrusion Multiplier/Flow Rate right now. I did use a calibration cube after my last reply to you and found out I would out of calibration for my steps/mm for X and Z axis and Extruder. Got them dialed back in. I'll see if I can get my dimensional accuracy back before going to sleep tonight.", "Sounds good. comments:
[["Captain's log, Stardate 5463.3:
After two weeks of shore leave on Earth, the upgrades to our sensors were completed and we began calibrations while still in system. To our surprise the new sensors detected an alien ship orbiting our eighth planet Neptune.
We proceeded to Neptune immediately under alert status to challenge the hidden starship, but we soon discovered why it had not been noticed before.The strange vessel was completely derelict, with only the smallest of residual energies detected and covered in stellar dust. According to Mr Spock's analysis the vessel is some 3000 years old. It has quietly orbited Neptune for almost that entire time just waiting to be discovered.
Mr Scott has analyzed our penetrating scans and believes that most of the technology is significantly less advanced than our own, though he does point out several anomalies such as a strange drive system that does not appear to be a conventional warp-drive.We are about to send an away team to investigate the those anomalies and try to determine the ship's origin.Mr Spock is also interested in a collection he detected of several hundred slab-like formations made of a carbon-based material deep within the ship.Visit my DA for more:
https://www.deviantart.com/dog42a/art/An-Unexpected-Find-925104799"]]
